@muelli 
If you want to make a FOSS Joplin on F-Droid, you can just change the build script on F-Droid, such as running `yarn remove react-native-camera` before building it. For people who doesn't care about FOSS, they can still download the original version on GitHub or Google Play. I remember that some apps also provide FOSS version even if they are on Google play. They remove the non-FOSS code by running a script before building it on F-Droid.
That said, the best way is to replace `react-native-camera` with `react-native-vision-camera`.

@m10d I'd leave the recommendation to @laurent22 â€“ but if you want to avoid the re-install, you can simply add [my repo](https://apt.izzysoft.de/fdroid) to your F-Droid client â€“ for NeoStore, you'd only need to enable it as it's already pre-configured there. My repo has not the same prestige, purity etc. as F-Droid has, but comes quite close. The APKs it serves are the ones signed by the resp. developers, so usually you can cross-update from an install you've made in the past via Play/Aurora.

That said, there's another minor difference between the Joplin versions from F-Droid and from my repo: the one in F-Droid is the "pure F/LOSS" variant, while the one in mine comes with so-called Anti-Features, as Laurent includes some proprietary libraries for additional features. You should keep that in mind to â€“ as e.g. MLKit brings in some Google-ties again, which you won't have with the F-Droid builds.

That said you see that at least concerning transparency, I'm fully with F-Droid. Well, I should, being one of the F-Droid maintainers, right? :wink:

@IzzySoft, we're experimenting again with creating separate APKs for different architectures, which are available there for example:

https://github.com/laurent22/joplin-android/releases/tag/android-v3.2.2

Would that help with your IzzyOnDroid repository?

@barthalion Thanks for the feedback. I'm not using Joplin at all, so it would be preferred if someone else that knows the app and can notice when something is broken would maintain it.  
For me, Flatpak packaging was kind of novelty and for being able to test it in a sandbox environment.

Nonetheless, I updated the [manifest](https://github.com/tinywrkb/flatpaks/blob/master/org.joplinapp.joplin/org.joplinapp.joplin.yaml) and that should be a bit more in line with Flathub submission, and this fixes an issue with the StatusNotifierItem system tray and the settings folder.

@laurent22 The external editor function will not work as intended with the Flatpak app, that's unless you'll be able to make use of the Portal API, so this should be taken into before Flathub publishing. Would it be acceptable to ship Joplin with this feature broken? adding an influx of users opening bug reports and complaining about it?

